Introduction
1.1 Purpose The purpose of this Vendor Security Policy is to establish guidelines and requirements for the secure selection, management, and ongoing monitoring of third-party vendors who have access to or process sensitive information on behalf of {name}. This policy aims to protect the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of our information assets.
1.2 Scope This policy applies to all vendors who provide products or services to {name} and have access to sensitive information, including but not limited to customer data, intellectual property, and confidential business information.
1.3 Policy Owner The {name} Information Security Department is the owner of this policy and is responsible for its maintenance and updates.
1.4 Policy Review This policy will be reviewed annually or as necessary to ensure its effectiveness and compliance with applicable laws, regulations, and industry standards.
Vendor Management
2.1 Vendor Selection The selection of vendors should be based on their ability to meet our security requirements and comply with applicable laws and regulations. The selection process should include a thorough evaluation of the vendor's security controls, policies, and practices.
2.2 Vendor Risk Assessment Prior to engaging with a vendor, a risk assessment should be conducted to identify and assess potential security risks associated with the vendor's products, services, and access to our information assets. The risk assessment should consider factors such as the sensitivity of the information involved, the vendor's security posture, and their track record in protecting sensitive information.
2.3 Due Diligence Due diligence activities should be performed to validate the accuracy and completeness of the information provided by the vendor. This may include reviewing the vendor's security certifications, conducting site visits, and obtaining references from other customers.
2.4 Vendor Contracting Contracts with vendors should include specific provisions related to information security, confidentiality, data protection, and compliance with applicable laws and regulations. These provisions should clearly define the responsibilities and obligations of both parties regarding security controls, incident response, breach notification, and termination of the agreement.
2.5 Ongoing Vendor Management Regular monitoring of vendor performance and security controls should be conducted to ensure ongoing compliance with our security requirements. This may include periodic security assessments, audits, and performance reviews.
2.6 Termination of Vendor Relationships Procedures should be in place to terminate vendor relationships in a secure manner when necessary. This should include the removal of vendor access to our systems, the return or destruction of sensitive information, and the notification of any affected parties.
Security Requirements
3.1 Information Security Management System (ISMS) Requirements Vendors should have an established Information Security Management System (ISMS) based on recognized industry standards such as ISO 27001. The ISMS should include policies, procedures, and controls to manage the security of their organization and the information assets entrusted to them.
3.2 Physical Security Vendors should implement appropriate physical security measures to protect our information assets from unauthorized access, theft, damage, or destruction. This may include access controls, video surveillance, visitor management, and secure disposal of physical media.
3.3 Access Controls Vendors should implement access controls to ensure that only authorized individuals can access our systems and data. This includes strong user authentication mechanisms, least privilege principles, and regular access reviews.
3.4 Data Protection and Privacy Vendors should implement measures to protect the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of our data throughout its lifecycle. This includes encryption of sensitive data in transit and at rest, secure data storage and backup, and compliance with applicable data protection and privacy laws.
3.5 Incident Response and Reporting Vendors should have an incident response plan in place to effectively detect, respond to, and recover from security incidents. They should also promptly report any security incidents involving our information assets and cooperate with our incident response team as needed.
3.6 Business Continuity and Disaster Recovery Vendors should have business continuity and disaster recovery plans in place to ensure the continued availability of our products or services in the event of a disruption. These plans should be regularly tested and updated to address emerging threats and vulnerabilities.
3.7 Security Awareness and Training Vendors should provide security awareness and training programs to their employees to ensure their understanding of security risks, policies, and procedures. These programs should be regularly updated and reinforced.
3.8 Audit and Compliance Vendors should cooperate with our internal and external audit processes and provide necessary evidence to demonstrate compliance with applicable laws, regulations, and industry standards. This may include allowing on-site audits, providing documentation, and participating in compliance assessments.
Security Assessments
4.1 Vendor Self-Assessment Vendors should periodically conduct self-assessments of their security controls and practices to ensure ongoing compliance with our security requirements. The results of these assessments should be shared with us upon request.
4.2 Third-Party Security Assessments We reserve the right to conduct security assessments of our vendors to verify their compliance with our security requirements. These assessments may include on-site visits, document reviews, and interviews with vendor personnel.
4.3 Penetration Testing and Vulnerability Assessments Vendors may be subject to periodic penetration testing and vulnerability assessments to identify and remediate security weaknesses. Prior notification will be provided to the vendor to ensure minimal disruption to their operations.
4.4 Security Incident Response Testing Vendors may be required to participate in security incident response testing exercises to assess their preparedness and coordination in responding to security incidents. This may involve simulated incidents and coordination with our incident response team.
4.5 Compliance Assessments Vendors may be subject to compliance assessments to evaluate their adherence to applicable laws, regulations, and industry-specific requirements. These assessments may cover areas such as data protection, privacy, intellectual property protection, export control, and anti-bribery and corruption.
Compliance with Laws and Regulations
5.1 Data Protection Laws Vendors should comply with applicable data protection laws and regulations, including but not limited to the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA), and other relevant data protection frameworks.
5.2 Intellectual Property Protection Vendors should respect intellectual property rights and protect our confidential information, trade secrets, trademarks, copyrights, and patents from unauthorized disclosure, use, or reproduction.
5.3 Industry-Specific Regulations Vendors operating in regulated industries should comply with industry-specific regulations and standards, such as financial regulations (e.g., PCI DSS for payment card data security) or healthcare regulations (e.g., HIPAA for protected health information).
5.4 Export Control and Sanctions Vendors should comply with export control laws and economic sanctions imposed by relevant governmental authorities. They should not engage in activities that violate export control regulations or facilitate prohibited transactions.
5.5 Anti-Bribery and Corruption Vendors should adhere to anti-bribery and corruption laws and regulations, including the U.S. Foreign Corrupt Practices Act (FCPA) and the U.K. Bribery Act. They should not offer, promise, or provide bribes, kickbacks, or any other form of improper advantage to our employees or third parties.
Incident Response and Breach Notification
6.1 Incident Response Plan Vendors should have a documented incident response plan that outlines the steps to be taken in the event of a security incident. The plan should include procedures for incident detection, containment, eradication, and recovery.
6.2 Reporting Security Incidents Vendors should promptly report any security incidents involving our information assets to our designated incident response contact. The report should include a detailed description of the incident, the potential impact, and any remedial actions taken or planned.
6.3 Breach Notification In the event of a data breach or unauthorized disclosure of our sensitive information, vendors should notify us without undue delay and in accordance with applicable laws and regulations. The notification should include the nature of the breach, the affected data, and any mitigation measures implemented.
Confidentiality and Non-Disclosure
7.1 Confidentiality Agreement Vendors should sign a confidentiality agreement that outlines their responsibilities regarding the protection of our confidential information. The agreement should prohibit the unauthorized use, disclosure, or reproduction of our confidential information.
7.2 Non-Disclosure Agreement Vendors should sign a non-disclosure agreement that prohibits the unauthorized disclosure of any non-public information shared with them during the course of our business relationship.
Documentation and Records Management
8.1 Vendor Documentation Vendors should maintain documentation related to their security controls, policies, procedures, and audits. These documents should be made available to us upon request to verify compliance with our security requirements.
8.2 Record Keeping Vendors should maintain records related to their engagement with us, including contracts, assessments, incident reports, and any other relevant documentation. These records should be retained for a defined period in accordance with applicable laws and regulations.
8.3 Retention and Destruction Vendors should establish procedures for the secure retention and destruction of our sensitive information in accordance with applicable legal, regulatory, and contractual requirements. This includes secure disposal of physical and electronic media containing sensitive data.
Training and Awareness
9.1 Vendor Security Awareness Program Vendors should have a security awareness program in place to educate their employees about security risks, best practices, and our specific security requirements. The program should be regularly updated and reinforced.
9.2 Training Requirements Vendors should ensure that their employees who have access to our systems or sensitive information receive appropriate training on security controls, data protection, incident response, and compliance with our policies.
9.3 Documentation and Reporting Vendors should maintain records of security training provided to their employees and periodically report on the training activities and completion rates.
Policy Non-Compliance
10.1 Non-Compliance Reporting Vendors should promptly report any known or suspected non-compliance with this policy or any security incidents involving our information assets.
10.2 Consequences of Non-Compliance Failure to comply with this policy may result in termination of the vendor relationship, legal action, and other appropriate measures as deemed necessary.
10.3 Escalation Process An escalation process should be established to address and resolve any disputes or disagreements related to the interpretation or enforcement of this policy. The escalation process should include designated points of contact from both parties and a mechanism for escalation to senior management if necessary.
